Botswana 2021-06-01 H7: Vaccination policy 2G 4G As of June 7, 2021, according to the U.S. Embassy in Botswana, Oxford University-AstraZeneca, Moderna, Sinovac, and Pfizer BioNTech have been approved for use. Janssen (Johnson&Johnson) and Gamaleya (Sputnik V) may be used in Botswana in the coming months. The rollout planned through COVAX will provide 100,800 vaccines for the country. 24,000 AstraZeneca doses have been delivered according to COVAX. Botswana announced the delivery of an additional 38,400 AstraZeneca doses from COVAX. The Government of Botswana reports 30,000 Covishield vaccines from India were received in early March and 200,000 doses of Sinovac were delivered on April 25. 19,890 Pfizer doses were received through COVAX in early June. Botswana began its vaccination campaign on March 26-7. They have opened vaccinations as of May 10 for those over 65, followed by those aged 55-64. They will prioritize those over 65 and those over 55 with underlying health conditions as more vaccines become available. Persons over 18 may already register on the vaccine registration webpage for future availability as eligibility expands. Government officials are being vaccinated, as confirmed on the government’s Twitter. https://web.archive.org/web/20210613032613/https://www.gov.uk/foreign-travel-advice/botswana/coronavirus https://web.archive.org/web/20210613032637/https://bw.usembassy.gov/covid-19-information/ https://web.archive.org/web/20210613062420/https://dhis2sms.gov.bw/vaccine/ https://web.archive.org/web/20210613053303/https://twitter.com/BWGovernment?ref_src=twsrc%5Egoogle%7Ctwcamp%5Eserp%7Ctwgr%5Eauthor

Canada 2021-06-04 H7: Vaccination policy 5G 4G As of 4 june 2021, 11:22AM EDT, according to the CTV news unofficial vaccine tracker, 22,709,722 Canadians [60% of the total national population and 68% of the vaccine-eligible population aged 12+] have received at least one dose of an approved COVID-19 vaccine – Moderna, Pfizer or AstraZeneca (no longer being offered as a first dose). Johnson & Johnson (J&J) Janssen vaccine has been approved, but shipments have not been distributed pending a quality control check. 2,481,530 Canadians [6.5% of total pop.] are fully vaccinated against COVID-19 having received two doses. Vaccinations were initially targeted on three priority groups: A. key workers (front-line health, education, emergency response), B. clinically vulnerable groups (indigenous communities, prisoners, homeless persons, those with medical conditions, adults in some neighbourhoods with high % of covid cases, pregnant women), C. elderly groups (residents of long-term care facilities/retirement homes first, then all seniors wherever they live). With all provinces and territories now making vaccinations available to ages as young as 12, code now at 5 = universal. See CTV news and Globe and Mail newspaper websites, archived: https://web.archive.org/web/20210604163830/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-covid-19-vaccine-rollout-in-canada-by-province-explainer/ https://web.archive.org/web/20210604164149/https://www.ctvnews.ca/health/coronavirus/coronavirus-vaccination-tracker-how-many-people-in-canada-have-received-shots-1.5247509

France 2021-06-09 C8: International travel controls 2 3 New regulations for entry to France were implemented on 9 June, with a system of green/orange/red list countries and different rules for travelers arriving from these lists, and exceptions for certain classes of traveler. Full details at https://web.archive.org/web/20210612160728/https://www.diplomatie.gouv.fr/fr/conseils-aux-voyageurs/informations-pratiques/article/coronavirus-covid-19 In summary: "“Green List”" - travellers from a country in the European area or from Australia, South Korea, Israel, Japan, Lebanon, New Zealand, and Singapore, are not subject to "“compelling reasons”" requirements for visiting France. Must provide evidence of a negative PCR test taken within 72 hours before departure, OR proof of complete vaccination with an EMA-approved vaccine. "“Orange List”" - from all countries not specified in other lists, must: - all must present negative results of a PCR test taken 72 hours before departure or an antigen test taken 48 hours before departure - vaccinate travelers not subject to "“compelling reasons”" test for entry - unvaccinated travelers are subject to "“compelling reasons”“, and must self-isolate for 7 days after arrival”“Red List”" - travelers from a country listed in the order of the Ministry of Health identifying the areas of active circulation of the epidemic or the spread of variants (currently Argentina, Bahrain, Bangladesh, Bolivia, Brazil, Chile, Colombia, Costa Rica, India, Nepal, Pakistan, South Africa, Sri Lanka, Suriname, Turkey, Uruguay) must: - have a "“compelling reason”" to visit France - negative results of PCR test taken up to 48 hours before departure - mandatory antigen test on arrival - mandatory 10 day quarantine on arrival, unless fully vaccinated in which case 7-day self isolation The "“Compelling Reasons”" allows the following to enter France: French nationals, their spouses and children, nationals of the European area as well as their spouses and children having their principal residence in France or who join, in transit through France, their main residence in a country of the European area or the country of which they are nationals.
